50|$|By {{the late}} 1980s, the Communist Party—and indeed, nearly all other {{institutions}} in Romania—had become completely subordinated to Ceaușescu's will. This was {{in contrast to}} the situation in other Communist countries. Most ruling Communist Party leaders were merely first among equals, even with the great power that came with their posts. Although Ceaușescu was a national Communist, his absolute control over the country and the pervasiveness of the cult led several non-Romanian observers to describe his regime as one of <b>the</b> <b>closest</b> <b>things</b> <b>to</b> an old-style Stalinist regime.|$|R
